In the decade preceding the signing of the Declaration of Independence, the villains were the Stamp Act and the Writs of Assistance Act.
Here is the backstory:In 1765, when the British government was looking for creative ways to tax the colonists, Parliament enacted the Stamp Act.
Answer: The Writs of Assistance Act.
Parliament repealed the Stamp Act in 1766, but it had caused lasting harm to the king.
Section 505 of the Patriot Act permits federal agents to bypass the requirements of the Fourth Amendment and to issue their own search warrants.